<title type="html"><![CDATA[triangle channel problems: blargg are you there?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=874&amp;p=7809#p7809"><![CDATA[
It's much simpler to just treat triangle frequencies above 20kHz as silent (or more correctly, as 50% amplitude, i.e. send 7.5 to the DAC). With the low 3 bits of $400B set to 0, these low values for $400A yield the following frequencies:<br /><br />0 55.9 kHz<br />1 28.0 kHz<br />2 18.6 kHz<br />3 14.0 kHz<br />...<br /><br />You could treat the first two or three entries as being inaudible, depending on how good your hearing is.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=17">blargg</a> — Wed Dec 28, 2005 8:40 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
